ons":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESeveral factors affect nephrotoxicity risk, with \u003Cstrong\u003Evasoconstriction\u003C/strong\u003E being a key risk factor as it reduces renal blood flow and glomerular filtration rate, increasing the risk of drug-induced kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevated serum albumin\u003C/strong\u003E is actually protective since hypoalbuminaemia increases free drug concentrations and toxicity risk. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased total body water\u003C/strong\u003E is also protective because reduced body water (common in elderly patients) increases drug concentrations. \u003Cstrong\u003ERenal vasodilation\u003C/strong\u003E is protective by maintaining renal blood flow. \u003Cstrong\u003EReduced serum creatinine\u003C/strong\u003E suggests normal kidney function, whereas elevated creatinine indicates existing kidney dysfunction and higher risk. Other risk factors include dehydration, advanced age, and concurrent nephrotoxic medications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Renal vasoconstriction increases nephrotoxicity risk by reducing renal blood flow and glomerular filtration","Reduced total body water increases drug concentrations and nephrotoxicity risk","Hypoalbuminaemia increases free drug concentrations and nephrotoxicity risk"],"references":["Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98016"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15029"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98016","links":{"self":"ht